![Sandy shores with effective protection of the connected land-sea interface can be maintained in natural/near natural ecological condition. © [Tash must let us know]{.mark}](imgs/PIC_20090810_umlalazi_beach_dunes.png)

[**Port photo?** **Mining photo?**]{.mark}

Mining, coastal development, trawling and mariculture ([check linefishing appears to have higher than 'sea-based aquaculture' in Table23]{.mark}) have the highest impact scores among the 31 pressures included in the assessment of ecological condition and contributed to [severely modified and very severely modified]{.mark} ecological condition in some areas [@sink2019]. Fishing is the greatest driver of modified ecological condition in the offshore environment, whereas coastal development and fishing are the greatest drivers of ecosystem modification in inshore ecosystems. Flow reduction, waste water discharge and lethal shark control measures also drive high levels of ecosystem modification in some areas.

<!-- Hotspots of degradation and cumulative impacts are often driven by the location of ports and harbours, which increase access for fishing, alter shorelines and circulation, increase pollution, and facilitate the introduction and spread of invasive species. Port and harbour location therefore warrants careful consideration. Areas of poor ecological condition include parts of the southwest Atlantic shelf edge and the inner shelf of much of the western Cape, and parts of the south coast and shelf and KwaZulu-Natal Bight (@fig-condition_benthic). -->

![Restored flows, improved bycatch and waste water management and further reductions of lethal shark control measures could improve ecological condition in parts of the KwaZulu-Natal Bight. This mesophotic reef is the uThukela MPA. © ACEP Surrogacy project, Kerry Sink.](imgs/uThukela_condition_ACEP.png)

## Groundtruthing ecological condition

Few cumulative impact studies validate their assessments of ecological condition, and groundtruthing ecological condition was a recommendation of the 2018 NBA. Smit et al. (2023) identified suitable indicators for condition assessments and defined reference conditions for rocky reef ecosystems, an important step in ecosystem assessment [@keith2013]. Subsequently, Smit et al. (2024) used rocky reef ecological data to compare reference conditions from well established MPAs against sites with varying cumulative pressures. [\[This was later expanded to over 1000 baited remote underwater stereo-video samples across ten MPAs spanning three ecoregions to assess functional diversity patterns at a broader scale (Smit et al. 2026).(cut?)\]]{.mark}

Results showed that ecological condition was significantly but weakly correlated with NBA cumulative impact scores, with notable discrepancies at finer scales, where some reefs were in better condition than predicted while others were worse (Smit et al. 2024). The cumulative impact scores performed better as a proxy for the condition of fish communities than for benthic communities [@smit2024]. Although the cumulative impact map was an effective proxy at broad scales, the findings highlighted the need for finer-scale pressure mapping and ecological data to improve ecological condition maps and support more accurate spatial assessments.

![Highly protected zones within MPAs can be used as reference areas to support the calibration of ecological condition. This reef is within the De Hoop MPA. © Steve Benjamin.](imgs/DeHoop_MPA_Steve_Benjamin.png)

## Approach {#sec-approach}

Ecological condition in the marine realm is assessed by intersecting the spatial maps of pressures on biodiversity with the ecosystem map by following the approach shown in @fig-condition_graphic. The assessment used the individual and combined impact of 31 mapped pressures [@majiedt2019] to assess ecological condition through the development of an ecosystem-pressure matrix [@sink2019].

![Schematic illustrating how ecological condition is mapped in the marine realm.](imgs/condition_calculation_graphic.jpg){#fig-condition_graphic}

To develop the ecosystem-pressure matrix, expert scoring of 'functional impact' and 'recovery' is conducted by experts supported by a synthesis of information on [pressures on marine biodiversity](marine_pressures.qmd), using a guided group consensus method approach that was adapted from [Teck et al. (2010)](https://doi.org/10.1890/09-1173.1) [@teck2010], to develop impact scores per activity for each ecosystem functional group [@sink2019].

::: {#box2 .callout-note .freshwater collapse="false" title="Box 2. Scoring of functional impact and recovery as part of an ecosystem-pressure matrix."}
**'Functional impact'** is a broad evaluation of the degree to which the natural state of any given ecosystem (including constituent species, community structure, physical habitat structure and ecosystem function) is impacted by a specific pressure. This component incorporates the issue of spatial scale or extent of a single act of an activity (pressure event), and impacts on trophic structure of communities. Experts evaluated the functional impact of a specific pressure to each broad ecosystem group, based on their knowledge, the support of international and local literature, and guided by the 0-10 scale in @tbl-impact_scores.

**'Recovery'** is a measure of the time required for the ecosystem (including affected species, physical habitat structure, and community trophic structure) to return to a natural state following cessation of disturbance by a given activity. As above, experts evaluated the recovery based on their knowledge, the support of literature, and guided by the 0-10 scale in @tbl-impact_scores.


::: {#tbl-impact_scores .cell .plain tbl-cap='Scoring guidelines used in the assessment of functional impact and recovery, as adapted from [Teck et al. (2010)](https://doi.org/10.1890/09-1173.1).'}
