Impact scores were calculated using a combination of the functional impact and recovery scores and scaled to values between 0 and 100 for ease of applying the IUCN methodology [\[which IUCN methodology? needs elaboration\]]{.mark}. Draft values were iteratively refined and updated with guidance of key specialists with local knowledge, until stable [consensus values]{.mark} were obtained [@sink2019].

Individual pressure impact layers were developed by combining the ecosystem-pressure matrix with the pressure intensity layer to produce maps showing the impact of each activity across the seascape. In this way, each pixel of the pressure impact layer represents the extent to which the ecosystem that exists there is impacted by the type and intensity of the pressure.

<!-- [jock has worked/edited until here, the remainder I'm just pasting in as is] -->

A cumulative impact score was derived by summing all the individual pressure impact scores at a specific site using the individual pressure impact layers, allowing for the development of a cumulative impact map showing the cumulative impact across the seascape [@sink2019].

To develop a map of ecosystem condition, the cumulative impact layer was recalibrated by assigning the cumulative impact scores into 4 condition categories (Box 1). This recalibration was achieved by distributing the mapped impact scores into 4 categories to align with the IUCN thresholds of more than 50%, 70% and 90% degradation or disruption based on natural breaks and expert inputs [@sink2019]. Numerical thresholds in the cumulative impact scores had to be defined in order to classify ecosystem degradation into 4 categories aligned to the IUCN degradation thresholds.

It must be clarified that although the assessment was conducted using 30 x 30 m pixels, this does not imply that the ecosystem map or the results are accurate to this level. Rather, this raster-based approach was used to allow for the calculations to be done at a sufficiently fine scale while accommodating the unique combinations of multiple pressures, pressure intensities, impacts and ecosystem types. The 30 x 30 m pixels reflect the size of the units used for the numerical calculations whereas the actual spatial accuracy is linked to the underlying accuracy of the ecosystem map and the pressure mapping. Improved finer-scale ecosystem and pressure mapping is a key priority for future assessments.

Smit et al. (2023, 2024, 2026)[@smit2023; @smit2024; @smit2026] made progress in field-based evaluations of site condition and this work must be expanded to other ecosystem functional groups. Such studies can be used to calibrate the cumulative impact scores and the classification thresholds used to subdivide categories. Further work is needed to investigate the use of different thresholds with better calibration guided by field surveys that measure condition representing the ideal approach.

Potential future improvements to the ecological condition mapping process include: ecological assessments. These include

• Revise scoring of impact and recovery scores with new literature and improved global collaboration.

• Refine scoring guidelines and definitions for improved clarity and repeatability.

• Develop multiple layers for different assessment components (e.g. benthic, pelagic, ongoing decline verses pressures that have stopped, abiotic vs biotic degradation). These should be tailored to different IUCN criteria.

• Apply learnings from research that can inform calibration of ecological condition.

• Increase knowledge on reference state of marine ecosystems using a broader diversity of indicators and a broader range of ecosystem functional groups.

• Continue to test and validate indicators for condition assessments, and in response to multiple pressures

• Increase transparency and repeatability in assessing condition.

• Explore application of critically modified category in marine realm (beyond shores) and novel or anthropogenic ecosystem types as defined by the IUCN global ecosystem typology.

• Increase alignment of condition categories (and condition adjusted representation approaches in protection level assessments) across realms where feasible.

